    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-4138361">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-4138361">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4138361)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4138361">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="4980602"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1549044457 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Feb 2019 18:07</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4138361">
									

<p>I think the idea of 049 post-ΩK is an almost automatically successful idea, but I am in the minority here and slightly let down at the execution. I'm trying to temper my reaction considering maybe such a let-down is almost just as inevitable as the idea is good, given the giant ingredients at play here.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Nitpicks</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>To me, the classic character has become a shell of itself and isn't interesting to me anymore. It's not that you've just shot him in the chest, it's that you've declawed him. His expertise is no longer the source of his effectiveness as a character, but is relegated to be a purely participatory act of pseudo-inclusion for his psychological disposition &#8212; something the Foundation containment staff and Ethics Committee perhaps shouldn't be concerned with. I also can't help but see the picture of 049 helping direct Foundation surgeons as unintentionally humorous. All in all, I guess I'd just rather not see the classic character this way. But that's probably the point of the tale.</p>
<p>I have some medical nitpicks that will be of no interest to you or anyone else:</p>
<ul>
<li>I am confused as to why anesthesia doesn't work post-ΩK. It is either general or local; local works on the nerve cells and keeps them from telling your brain you are in pain. General depresses the control centers of the brain so that it can't care if the nerves are telling it that. I don't see how the end of mortality would render either of these mechanisms ineffective.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>049 is misdiagnosed as having Borderline Personality Disorder. Borderlines are labile in their personalities; extremely outgoing and then unapologetically hostile once you do something they don't approve of. They are also professionals at mind games and using manipulation to get what they want from others, most characteristically injuring themselves to that end. Their behavior continues to be attention-seeking throughout the disorder. I don't see that in this 049; he is not labile, simply steadily depressed, and he has a defeatist attitude by the end, not one that is attempting manipulation for its gain. <strong>Edit:</strong> I agree with Doctor North above and they are right; the above described behavior is commonly out of a fear of abandonment. Gesturing suicide is the usual tactic to get the attention they want.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>I'm not sure why surgeons are still performing surgery post-death. Perhaps for symptomatic relief &#8212; from painful conditions comes to mind &#8212; but we've already been told that anesthetics don't work in this reality (fixing the previous nitpick would fix this one too). It's not clear to me how they could justify such kid-gloves for the psychological state of an anomaly that's historically dedicated to insensitivity for humanity, while apparently disregarding or putting to vote the pain that would accompany performing unnecessary surgery (no one is going to die from not doing the surgery) on fully-feeling and unavoidably waking people. I can't at present think of a procedure that would be worth it pain-wise in this scenario. <strong>Edit:</strong> <em>Maybe</em> amputation or plastic surgery. But I don't think you'd need a 049 consult for those (certainly not the plastics!).</li>
</ul>
<p>Novote for now but I'll come back to it, because it really is such a great combo of ingredients.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
